dialogue_english: The vada is gone...
context: Vadivelu attempts to steal a vada (snack) but loses it to a crow unexpectedly.

dialogue_tanglish: Naanum rowdy dhaan, naanum rowdy dhaan!
dialogue_english: I am also a rowdy! I am also a rowdy!
context: Screaming in a police station to get arrested and gain street credibility.

dialogue_english: The building is strong, but the basement is weak.
context: Boasting about physical appearance while admitting to poor health/stamina.

dialogue_english: Oh my! They have all gathered, they have all gathered!
context: Reacting to a group of enemies or ghosts gathering in one spot.

dialogue_english: Why is there blood? It is the same blood.
context: Trying to diffuse a tense situation after getting beaten up, implying unity.

dialogue_english: Sona mutha... is it gone?
context: Realizing that he has been tricked and lost all his money/status.

dialogue_english: Don't... it hurts... I will cry!
context: Begging someone to stop beating him in a childish manner.

dialogue_tanglish: Risk edukrathu ellam engalukku rusk sapdra maathiri.
dialogue_english: Taking risks is like eating a rusk for me.
context: Bragging about bravery before doing something incredibly stupid.

dialogue_english: Buddy... he has set a trap!
context: Realizing a friend or enemy has successfully tricked him.

dialogue_tanglish: Hello Dubai-ah? En brother Mark irukara?
dialogue_english: Hello Dubai? Is my brother Mark there?
context: Pretending to make an international call to impress locals.

dialogue_english: You don't need to pull the nail.
context: Telling someone their 'help' is making things worse, so just do nothing.

dialogue_english: You aren't doing any comedy with me, are you?
context: Suspicious that people are pranking him.

dialogue_english: I was just shocked!
context: Exaggerating a reaction to a surprising event.

dialogue_tanglish: Oorukkulla oru all in all azhaguraja.
dialogue_english: An all-in-all beauty king in the town.
context: Referring to himself as a jack-of-all-trades.

dialogue_tanglish: Sothulayum adi vangiyachu, sethulayum adi vangiyachu.
dialogue_english: Got beaten up in the food, got beaten up in the mud too.
context: Lamenting that he gets beaten up wherever he goes.

dialogue_tanglish: Ippo enna romba mukkiyam? Uyira? Maanama?
dialogue_english: What is important now? Life? Or Dignity?
context: Deciding whether to run away (save life) or stay and fight (save dignity).

dialogue_english: If not Trisha, then Nayanthara.
context: Moving on quickly from a rejection; plenty of fish in the sea.

dialogue_english: Tiger is coming! Tiger is coming!
context: Playing a prank that eventually turns real (Boy who cried wolf scenario).

dialogue_english: Brother, has the tea not come yet?
context: Asking irrelevantly about tea while in a serious or dangerous situation.

dialogue_english: Shall I leave...?
context: Trying to escape a situation quietly before getting caught.

dialogue_english: Cool down... cool down.
context: Trying to calm an angry mob or person he has offended.

dialogue_english: Is that you?
context: Recognizing someone who has changed significantly or done something unexpected.

dialogue_tanglish: Sing in the rain... I am sing in the rain.
dialogue_english: Sing in the rain... I am singing in the rain.
context: Singing happily unaware of impending doom.

dialogue_english: I also didn't come for the fight.
context: Backing out of a fight he started.

dialogue_english: We must plan and do it.
context: Advising that any task must be executed with a proper plan.

dialogue_english: Look at how I was, and look at what I have become.
context: Lamenting a fall from grace or loss of dignity.

dialogue_tanglish: Kaakaiku veippel, aana ezhai kuzhandhaiku veika maatel?
dialogue_english: You will feed rice to the crows, but you won't feed a poor child?
context: Questioning social superstitions vs humanitarian aid.

dialogue_english: If you die today, milk (ritual) tomorrow.
context: Highlighting the fleeting nature of life.

dialogue_english: Win or lose, twirl your mustache.
context: Encouraging confidence regardless of the outcome.

dialogue_tanglish: Confusion of the constitution of the institution...
dialogue_english: Confusion of the constitution of the institution...
context: Using fake complex English to confuse someone.

dialogue_tanglish: Ivanunga moonja patha nallavanga maari theriyala.
dialogue_english: Looking at their faces, they don't seem like good people.
context: Judging a group of people who look suspicious.

dialogue_english: Take diversion.
context: Reading a road sign literally to change the topic or path.

dialogue_tanglish: Saavukku bayanthavan than sivan koviluku povan.
dialogue_english: Only he who fears death goes to the Shiva temple.
context: Mocking someone's sudden religious turn due to fear.

dialogue_english: Desire, dosa, papad, vada.
context: Listing food items rhythmically to distract or annoy.

dialogue_english: If it goes, let it go, man.
context: Advising someone to let go of their worries.

dialogue_english: Let us learn, let us teach.
context: A slogan for education and spreading knowledge.

dialogue_english: What, this is so childish?
context: Criticizing someone's immature behavior.

dialogue_english: He who drinks coffee will go into a coma.
context: Spreading fake medical facts to scare people.

dialogue_english: Do they rent a room just to think like this?
context: Wondering how someone came up with such a stupid idea.

dialogue_english: You will come up well in life.
context: Sarcastic praise to someone doing something useless.

dialogue_tanglish: Yarume illatha kadaila yarukku da tea aathura?
dialogue_english: Who are you making tea for in an empty shop?
context: Questioning someone performing a task with no audience/customers.

dialogue_english: Did you see how he got caught?
context: Enjoying someone else getting caught in a trap.

dialogue_english: Minor has shot the bird!
context: Misinterpreting a situation where someone got shot/hurt.

dialogue_english: If you pray to God, you will get it.
context: Mocking blind faith without effort.

dialogue_english: I don't know what the reason is.
context: Feigning ignorance about a disaster he caused.

dialogue_english: Oh no, why are you doing this?
context: Reacting to someone destroying his plans.

dialogue_english: Son, you will do very well.
context: Blessing someone (often sarcastic).

dialogue_english: What kind of birth is this?
context: Questioning the absurdity of his current situation.

dialogue_tanglish: Vayasanalum un style um azhagum innum pogala.
dialogue_english: Even though you aged, your style and beauty hasn't faded.
context: Complimenting Rajinikanth (or himself/others) on aging gracefully.

dialogue_tanglish: Naan eppo varuven, epdi varuvennu yarukkum theriyathu.
dialogue_english: When I will come, how I will come, nobody knows.
context: Mimicking Rajinikanth's famous dialogue.

dialogue_english: Oh God... is that you?
context: Sarcastically praising someone who finally did something helpful.

dialogue_tanglish: Nallavanga dialogue reach aagum, aana late-a reach aagum.
dialogue_english: Good people's dialogues will reach, but it will reach late.
context: Justifying why his advice isn't appreciated immediately.

dialogue_english: Buddy, order a quarter (alcohol) for me.
context: Casual request to a friend in a bar setting.

dialogue_english: Friendship, man!
context: Proclaiming love for his friend (often while drunk or emotional).

dialogue_tanglish: Kadavule, Ajith Kumar padam patha maari iruke.
dialogue_english: Oh God, it feels like watching an Ajith Kumar movie.
context: Reacting to a stunt or a massive buildup.

dialogue_english: We are all terrors.
context: Joking about how 'scary' or 'tough' they are.

dialogue_tanglish: Nee poi love sonna paravala, neeye vedikka paaka pora.
dialogue_english: It's fine if you propose love, but you're just going to watch the fun.
context: Predicting that a friend's love life will be a disaster.

dialogue_english: Fact, fact, fact.
context: Agreeing completely with a statement.

dialogue_tanglish: Oorla pathu pathinanju friend vachirukavan ellam santhosama irukan.
dialogue_english: People with 10-15 friends are happy in this town.
context: Complaining that having just one friend (the hero) is torture.

dialogue_english: A drunkard's speech is gone by dawn.
context: Dismissing promises made while drunk.

dialogue_english: Come, let's go have a beer.
context: Solution to all problems: drinking beer.

dialogue_english: Oh no!
context: Standard reaction to something going wrong.

dialogue_english: Cash, wealth, dough, money money.
context: Singing about the importance of money.

dialogue_english: Nagaraj Chola MA MLA.
context: Introducing himself with a fake high-status title.

dialogue_tanglish: Unakku vandha ratham, enakku vandha thakkaali chutney ah?
dialogue_english: If you bleed it's blood, if I bleed is it tomato chutney?
context: Pointing out hypocrisy or double standards.

dialogue_english: Sir, what is this?
context: Questioning authority or a confused situation.

dialogue_english: Simran... Simran!
context: Calling out a girl's name (often mistakenly).

dialogue_english: He is a friend, man.
context: Defending a friend's stupid actions.

dialogue_english: Dear, do you wish to eat a laddu?
context: Asking if someone wants something very desirable (too good to be true).

dialogue_english: What buddy?
context: Casual greeting or inquiry.

dialogue_english: Did you roast me?
context: Asking if he just got insulted/mocked.

dialogue_english: Hey, are you crazy?
context: Reacting to someone's stupidity.

dialogue_english: This is the world.
context: Philosophical take on how unfair life is.

dialogue_english: You put on makeup and mesmerize me.
context: Flirting or commenting on a woman's appearance.

dialogue_english: Go and mind your business/livelihood.
context: Dismissing a crowd or useless people.
